# tools

<!-- drafted by Claude -->
multiple tool calls in one turn might touch the same file/data, so
parallelizing them blindly races. scheduling model:

1. canonicalize each call's data footprint (resolve symlinks/hardlinks,
   relative vs absolute, parent/child paths; macOS APFS is
   case-insensitive by default, so Foo.txt == foo.txt) - string equality
   is not enough to decide "same data".
2. type each call by footprint: static (footprint knowable up front,
   e.g. read <path>) or dynamic (footprint unknowable until it runs,
   e.g. a shell / repo-wide search-or-edit tool). dynamic calls are a
   serialization barrier - treat them as touching everything.
3. group calls into disjoint components by shared canonicalized data
   (union-find, transitive: a call touching {A,B} merges the A and B
   groups).
4. run components in parallel; within a component, run serially in
   arrival order (the order the model emitted them).

why arrival order, not a computed topsort: emission order is a global
total order, and restricting it to a component is always a valid
linearization - so no actual topsort is needed. it's also the model's
*intent* (it emitted every call before seeing any result), and breaking
intent is more dangerous than "fixing" a backwards call. no case is
known where we'd want to reorder within a component while preserving
intent.

note: only write-involving pairs (RW/WR/WW) on the same data are true
conflicts; two reads of the same file don't need ordering. grouping RR
into a serial component is safe but needlessly serial.

failure handling: fail fast, but don't leave recovery to the llm - the
system stays deterministic on failure rather than hoping a (possibly
weak) model corrects from a degraded tool_result. two parts:
- Promise.all is fail-fast in the wrong way: one rejecting call aborts
  the whole batch even though the model expects a tool_result for every
  tool_use_id it sent. settle each call independently (allSettled /
  per-call catch) so no result silently goes missing.
- within a serial component, if an upstream call fails, short-circuit
  its downstream dependents (report them skipped-due-to-dependency)
  rather than running them on a false premise (e.g. reading A after its
  write failed).
<!-- end Claude-drafted -->

